  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Compliance with Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Laws\n- Bank Secrecy Act\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- International regulations like FATF recommendations\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Implementing internal controls\n- Conducting periodic risk assessments\n- Training employees on AML procedures\n\n5. Sanctions Screening\n- Checking transactions against global sanctions lists\n- Preventing transactions with prohibited entities/individuals\n\n6. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Retaining documentation for specified periods\n- Ensuring data accessibility for regulatory review\n\nFailure to comply can result in significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges. These obligations aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the financial system.",
